### Operators
Operators are symbols used to perform operations on values or variables.

## Types of Operators
=> Arithmetic Operators
=> Comparison / Relational Operators
=> Logical Operators
=> Assignment Operators
=> Identity Operators
=> Membership Operators

1. Arithmetic Operators
Used to perform mathematical calculations.

a = 5, b = 2
| Operator | Description        | Example  | Output |
| -------- | ------------------ | -------- | ------ |
| `+`      | Addition           | `a + b`  | `7`    |
| `-`      | Subtraction        | `a - b`  | `3`    |
| `*`      | Multiplication     | `a * b`  | `10`   |
| `/`      | Division           | `a / b`  | `2.5`  |
| `%`      | Modulo (Remainder) | `a % b`  | `1`    |
| `**`     | Exponentiation     | `a ** b` | `25`   |
| `//`     | Floor Division     | `a // b` | `2`    |

2. Comparison / Relational Operators
Used to compare two values.
The result will always be True or False.

| Operator | Description              | Example  | Result |
| -------- | ------------------------ | -------- | ------ |
| `==`     | Equal to                 | `a == b` | `True` |
| `!=`     | Not equal to             | `a != b` | `True` |
| `>`      | Greater than             | `a > b`  | `True` |
| `<`      | Less than                | `a < b`  | `True` |
| `>=`     | Greater than or equal to | `a >= b` | `True` |
| `<=`     | Less than or equal to    | `a <= b` | `True` |

3. Logical Operators
Used to combine conditional statements.

| Operator | Description                                      | Example                 |
| -------- | ------------------------------------------------ | ----------------------- |
| `and`    | Returns `True` if both conditions are true       | `age > 18 and age < 30` |
| `or`     | Returns `True` if at least one condition is true | `age > 18 or age < 5`   |
| `not`    | Reverses the result                              | `not age > 18`          |

4.Assignment Operators
Used to assign and update variable values.

| Operator | Equivalent To   | Example  | Result |
| -------- | --------------- | -------- | ------ |
| `=`      | Assign value    | `x = 3`  | `3`    |
| `+=`     | `x = x + value` | `x += 3` | `8`    |
| `-=`     | `x = x - value` | `x -= 3` | `2`    |
| `*=`     | `x = x * value` | `x *= 3` | `15`   |
| `/=`     | `x = x / value` | `x /= 3` | `1.0`  |

5. Identity Operators
Used to check whether two variables refer to the same object in memory.

| Operator | Description                                 | Example      | Output |
| -------- | ------------------------------------------- | ------------ | ------ |
| `is`     | Returns `True` if both refer to same object | `a is b`     | `True` |
| `is not` | Returns `True` if different objects         | `a is not b` | `True` |

6.Membership Operators
Used to check if a value exists in a sequence (list, tuple, string, etc.).

| Operator | Description                            | Example               | Output |
| -------- | -------------------------------------- | --------------------- | ------ |
| `in`     | Returns `True` if value exists         | `"P" in "Python"`     | `True` |
| `not in` | Returns `True` if value does not exist | `"K" not in "Python"` | `True` |

